WEST NILE VIRUS, HUMAN CASES - ISRAEL (03)
******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
See Also
West Nile virus, human case - Israel 20000901.1469
West Nile virus, human cases - Israel (02) 20000903.1490
Date: Fri 15 Sep 2000
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Associated Press, Fri 15 Sep 2000 [edited

From mid-August to November, hundreds of millions of birds cross Israel as
they migrate from Europe to the warmer African climates. Some of them carry
West Nile virus. This virus is picked up by mosquitoes and spreads quickly
to humans, causing sickness ranging from a severe, flu-like symptoms to
deadly encephalitis, or inflammation of the brain. This year, Israel is in
the grip of a particularly severe outbreak of the disease, triggering a
health crisis that competes for headline space and talk-show time with
political turmoil and the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
As of yesterday, 120 cases had been identified, hundreds more are
suspected, and 8 people have died. No cases have so far been reported in
the West Bank or Gaza, according to Palestinian authorities, who are
nonetheless working to curb their mosquito population. [West Nile virus
was first identified in the blood of a patient in West Nile province,
Uganda, in 1937. Outbreaks have since occurred in 17 countries, including a
serious one in New York last year. The elderly and weak and those with
heart problems are at greatest risk of serious complications. Of those who
died, 7 were close to 80 years old. The latest victim, a 54-year-old woman,
suffered from a disease that suppressed her immune system, officials say.
Patients often become comatose before dying. For the young and healthy,
West Nile virus causes fever, head and muscle ache and a severe sore
throat. One 33-year-old woman, told Israel television she had been
hospitalized and is now in a wheelchair, but doctors give her good chances
of recovery.
The reason for this year's outbreak is still a mystery. One theory is that
the bird migratory period began earlier than usual. Israel does not have
more mosquitoes than normal, said Yossi Inbar, deputy director general of
the Environment Ministry. Mosquitoes multiply in standing water, and this
has been a dry year even by Israeli standards.
[Byline: Mark Matthews
